Go Bike Trip Data¶

By: Muneera Alshunaifi¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

This document explores Ford GoBike data in 2018. This data set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area in 2018. The purpose is to investigate which variable(s) has the most effect on trip duration of the users.

#convert time period, month, and weekday to category.

ordinal_var_dict = {'start_month_name': ['June','July','August','September','October','November','December'],
                    'period_day': ['Morning', 'Afternoon', 'Night'],
                    'start_weekday_name': ['Monday', 'Tuesday', 'Wednesday', 'Thursday', 'Friday', 'Saturday', 'Sunday']}

for var in ordinal_var_dict:
    ordered_var = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True,
                                                categories = ordinal_var_dict[var])
    bikes[var] = bikes[var].astype(ordered_var)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 1,863,721 bikes ride data from 2018 in the dataset with 11 features (ride duration, start and end time, start station id and name, end station id and name, bike id, customer type, birth year, and gender). then it becomes 8468 bikes ride with 11 features after dropping outliers. Most variables are string.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm most interested in figuring out what features are best for predicting the duration of the trip. Here are some questions I want to extract its answers from dataset:

  • When and where most trips taken?
  • Do Age and Sex , user type affect the duration and the locations?

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect that specific stations will have more bike rides rather than other stations and thats because of the station location, Also I am expecting that morning and afternoon rides are more than night rides due to rush hours. Also, I assume younger riders are more than older riders because of physical abilities. Moreover, I think that the other features: user type and sex will have effects on the duration.

Univariate Exploration¶

I'll start by looking at the distribution of the main variable of interest: time and start location

points =  bikes_top_st.shape[0]
usercounts =  bikes_top_st['user_type'].value_counts()
locs, labels = plt.xticks()

# print frequency on the bar chart
for loc, label in zip(locs, labels):
    count = usercounts[label.get_text()]
    pct_string = '{:0.2f}%'.format(100*count/points)
    plt.text(loc, count-8, pct_string, ha='center', color='b')

plt.title('Bike rides by User Types in top stations')
plt.xlabel('User Type')

plt.show()

From above figure we can find that 87.79% of user types are Subscriber or Member and the rest of users are Customer or casual, i think thats because of the pricing page where Subscribers pay less than Customers.
